DANIEL PATTERSON: If you
see the effort on the plate,

00:50:48.768 --> 00:50:50.130
we've done something wrong.

00:50:50.130 --> 00:50:52.890
So the work should
stay in the kitchen.

00:50:52.890 --> 00:50:55.010
And what's on the
plate should be easy.

00:50:55.010 --> 00:50:57.090
It should be like,
no one should have

00:50:57.090 --> 00:50:58.920
to wonder how to eat something.

00:50:58.920 --> 00:51:01.200
And this is just my own feeling.

00:51:01.200 --> 00:51:03.290
Or when they eat
it, they shouldn't

00:51:03.290 --> 00:51:05.180
wonder what they're eating.

00:51:05.180 --> 00:51:06.120
So we go for flavor.

00:51:06.120 --> 00:51:10.440
When you talk about
simplicity, simple is hard.

00:51:10.440 --> 00:51:16.180
Simple, to mean concentrated,
clear, distillation,

00:51:16.180 --> 00:51:19.130
of a flavor that's
just like a pinpoint

00:51:19.130 --> 00:51:22.650
and like a shock of
recognition, to deliver

00:51:22.650 --> 00:51:25.649
that every single time?

00:51:25.649 --> 00:51:26.440
That's really hard.

00:51:26.440 --> 00:51:27.960
And so that's really
what our focus is.

00:51:27.960 --> 00:51:29.293
And that comes from ingredients.

00:51:29.293 --> 00:51:30.380
It comes from technique.

00:51:30.380 --> 00:51:32.520
And it comes from
knowing when to stop,

00:51:32.520 --> 00:51:34.080
I think, a little bit, too.

00:51:34.080 --> 00:51:35.880
MALE SPEAKER: Over-manipulation.

00:51:35.880 --> 00:51:38.170
DANIEL PATTERSON: Yeah, I
mean, it's a tough thing.

00:51:38.170 --> 00:51:43.040
Because I think the second you
take a chicken and kill him,

00:51:43.040 --> 00:51:43.910
you manipulate it.

00:51:43.910 --> 00:51:45.470
And then you put it in the
oven, you manipulate it again.

00:51:45.470 --> 00:51:48.330
So you have roast chicken, which
is the least manipulated thing.

00:51:48.330 --> 00:51:50.730
But everything is manipulation.

00:51:50.730 --> 00:51:54.640
But for me, it's more a
matter of understanding

00:51:54.640 --> 00:51:59.880
the proper limits of a dish.

00:51:59.880 --> 00:52:03.000
Each dish has its own
moment where you just

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:06.570
need to have the
intuition to know

00:52:06.570 --> 00:52:08.670
when to stop, to add something.

00:52:08.670 --> 00:52:11.596
And I think intuition is
the hardest thing to teach,

00:52:11.596 --> 00:52:12.270
I think.

00:52:12.270 --> 00:52:13.665
MALE SPEAKER: Only
comes with time, right?

00:52:13.665 --> 00:52:15.255
DANIEL PATTERSON: Or
it doesn't come at all.

00:52:15.255 --> 00:52:16.590
MALE SPEAKER: Many
times, unfortunately.

00:52:16.590 --> 00:52:18.590
DANIEL PATTERSON: Yeah,
I mean, let's be honest.

00:52:18.590 --> 00:52:21.000
I think you can teach
anyone how to cook well.

00:52:21.000 --> 00:52:24.090
But there's a certain point
at which you can't really

00:52:24.090 --> 00:52:29.330
teach someone to make a
connection that's not already

00:52:29.330 --> 00:52:31.090
in place.

00:52:31.090 --> 00:52:32.920
But you can teach
someone to make

00:52:32.920 --> 00:52:35.100
a connection that
has been established.

00:52:35.100 --> 00:52:38.040
MALE SPEAKER: As a chef,
there are many things

00:52:38.040 --> 00:52:41.126
that people do in my kitchen
that have infuriated me.

00:52:41.126 --> 00:52:44.087
What is an example for you?

00:52:44.087 --> 00:52:45.420
DANIEL PATTERSON: You know what?

00:52:45.420 --> 00:52:53.584
It's funny because-- I mean--
I'm so much better than I was.

00:52:53.584 --> 00:52:55.000
But if you caught
me 10 years ago?

00:52:55.000 --> 00:52:56.450
Oh, my God.

00:52:56.450 --> 00:52:59.460
But even now, like
what just sends me

00:52:59.460 --> 00:53:02.590
through the roof
is just not caring.

00:53:02.590 --> 00:53:05.020
I feel like when people
come into a restaurant,

00:53:05.020 --> 00:53:06.660
they've given us their trust.

00:53:06.660 --> 00:53:07.800
And that trust is sacred.

00:53:07.800 --> 00:53:12.230
And when I feel like people
haven't taken that seriously,

00:53:12.230 --> 00:53:15.040
that's the only thing.

00:53:15.040 --> 00:53:17.800
We have so many
safety nets in place,

00:53:17.800 --> 00:53:21.060
it's almost impossible
for a mistake

00:53:21.060 --> 00:53:23.670
to get to the dining
room at this point

00:53:23.670 --> 00:53:26.650
because we have so many checks
and balances along the way.

00:53:26.650 --> 00:53:28.750
But not caring is
the only thing.

00:53:28.750 --> 00:53:30.940
So if you make a
mistake, we're human.

00:53:30.940 --> 00:53:31.690
We make mistakes.

00:53:31.690 --> 00:53:34.830
That's not something
that makes me upset.

00:53:34.830 --> 00:53:37.560
But not caring or not
trying hard enough

00:53:37.560 --> 00:53:39.320
is the thing that gets me.

00:53:39.320 --> 00:53:42.360
Because it's like, if you
don't want to work that hard,

00:53:42.360 --> 00:53:47.290
go to another restaurant
that has a simpler form where

00:53:47.290 --> 00:53:48.890
you don't have to
work that hard.

00:53:48.890 --> 00:53:50.340
Our form demands a lot of work.

00:53:50.340 --> 00:53:53.590
And it demands a lot of caring.

00:53:53.590 --> 00:53:57.340
And the caring is the thing
that is the most important.

00:53:57.340 --> 00:54:00.590
If you care and you make
a mistake, ah, it happens.

00:54:00.590 --> 00:54:04.259
And we get some young
cooks that come in.

00:54:04.259 --> 00:54:05.300
Sure, they make mistakes.

00:54:05.300 --> 00:54:06.300
They're not experienced.

00:54:06.300 --> 00:54:07.810
But a lot of heart.

00:54:07.810 --> 00:54:11.270
And that's what matters.

00:54:11.270 --> 00:54:14.590
MALE SPEAKER: How do
you feel about the epic

00:54:14.590 --> 00:54:17.000
issue with obesity
in this country,

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:20.840
the government's attempt
to either tax soda,

00:54:20.840 --> 00:54:25.300
or perhaps to
inspire people to eat

00:54:25.300 --> 00:54:26.920
better which I'm
certainly a fan of?

00:54:26.920 --> 00:54:28.590
But I'd love your
thoughts on that.

00:54:28.590 --> 00:54:31.720
You don't necessarily
deal with healthy eating

00:54:31.720 --> 00:54:34.450
as a focus in Coi.

00:54:34.450 --> 00:54:36.700
DANIEL PATTERSON: Yeah, it's
funny you mentioned that.

00:54:36.700 --> 00:54:38.450
So for about three
years, we've been

00:54:38.450 --> 00:54:40.552
working with Larkin
Street Youth Services.

00:54:40.552 --> 00:54:41.260
MALE SPEAKER: OK.

00:54:41.260 --> 00:54:45.100
DANIEL PATTERSON: And you get
hit up a lot in restaurants

00:54:45.100 --> 00:54:52.640
for, why don't you make
1,000 pieces of something

00:54:52.640 --> 00:54:56.940
on a shitty piece of toast
for the opera or something?

00:54:56.940 --> 00:54:59.760
And you feel nickel
and dimed a little bit.

00:54:59.760 --> 00:55:02.940
And I thought, well, why don't
we just take a lot of energy

00:55:02.940 --> 00:55:07.450
and put it in one place that
is doing work that we really

00:55:07.450 --> 00:55:11.147
believe in, that has our values.

00:55:11.147 --> 00:55:13.730
And this is an organization that
takes kids in off the street.

00:55:13.730 --> 00:55:16.380
They give them counseling
and job training

00:55:16.380 --> 00:55:18.315
and a place to stay and food.

00:55:18.315 --> 00:55:19.530
MALE SPEAKER: OK.

00:55:19.530 --> 00:55:21.520
DANIEL PATTERSON: And so we've
tried a lot of different things

00:55:21.520 --> 00:55:22.020
with them.

00:55:22.020 --> 00:55:24.910
But the thing that
worked best is I

00:55:24.910 --> 00:55:28.030
finally called them and said,
look, bring some kids over.

00:55:28.030 --> 00:55:29.540
We're closed on Mondays.

00:55:29.540 --> 00:55:31.470
I'll do a cooking class.

00:55:31.470 --> 00:55:34.750
And these are kids who grew up,
a lot of them, with processed

00:55:34.750 --> 00:55:36.690
food, without healthy food.

00:55:36.690 --> 00:55:40.580
A lot of things that
are so, so, basic to me,

00:55:40.580 --> 00:55:42.340
they've never seen before.

00:55:42.340 --> 00:55:45.607
And it wasn't like we were on
opposite sides of the table.

00:55:45.607 --> 00:55:46.940
Like, OK, everyone come on back.

00:55:46.940 --> 00:55:47.500
Here's some cutting boards.

00:55:47.500 --> 00:55:48.340
Here's some knives.

00:55:48.340 --> 00:55:50.520
Try not to cut your fingers off.

00:55:50.520 --> 00:55:52.040
And let's cook some food.

00:55:52.040 --> 00:55:52.730
Lets have fun.

00:55:52.730 --> 00:55:55.165
So the whole thing
is delicious and fun.

00:55:55.165 --> 00:55:57.530
And get people with A, a
taste memory of something

00:55:57.530 --> 00:55:59.160
that's good for them
that's delicious.

00:55:59.160 --> 00:56:01.180
Because if there's no
taste memory of good food,

00:56:01.180 --> 00:56:05.550
there's no way to reorient--
the way we're put together,

00:56:05.550 --> 00:56:08.105
if you grow up being
comforted by potato chips,

00:56:08.105 --> 00:56:09.480
potato chips is
what you're going

00:56:09.480 --> 00:56:13.041
to reach for in a time
of stress or crisis.

00:56:13.041 --> 00:56:14.790
And if someone gives
you a bowl of greens,

00:56:14.790 --> 00:56:17.530
but you have no
association with them?

00:56:17.530 --> 00:56:19.350
You're not going to crave them.

00:56:19.350 --> 00:56:21.800
But if you have a bowl of
greens that's delicious,

00:56:21.800 --> 00:56:25.410
and you associate it
with this very fun day

00:56:25.410 --> 00:56:27.610
that you're hanging
out with these people

00:56:27.610 --> 00:56:31.280
who you're living with, and then
you have this good experience,

00:56:31.280 --> 00:56:34.030
then you're like, oh,
I'd eat that again.

00:56:34.030 --> 00:56:35.940
Because it's not
just good, but it's

00:56:35.940 --> 00:56:38.830
connected to a good feeling.

00:56:38.830 --> 00:56:41.650
And then the other thing
is having some basic tools

00:56:41.650 --> 00:56:44.620
to feed themself at
home that good food.

00:56:44.620 --> 00:56:47.510
And so we started something
called The Cooking Project.

00:56:47.510 --> 00:56:51.020
And right now it's out of
San Francisco Cooking School.

00:56:51.020 --> 00:56:54.750
And it focuses tightly
on the Tenderloin,

00:56:54.750 --> 00:56:58.450
using products that they can
get in their neighborhood.

00:56:58.450 --> 00:57:00.650
We have a different chef
come every other week

00:57:00.650 --> 00:57:03.010
and teach them one
or two little things,

00:57:03.010 --> 00:57:04.940
things that they can
tell a story about,

00:57:04.940 --> 00:57:08.310
things that have meaning,
whether it's a pasta,

00:57:08.310 --> 00:57:11.600
we've had different
kinds of porridge,

00:57:11.600 --> 00:57:15.360
different kinds of
stews, salads, whatever.

00:57:15.360 --> 00:57:18.430
And then afterwards--
everyone makes all the food

00:57:18.430 --> 00:57:20.580
and they sit down
and eat it together.

00:57:20.580 --> 00:57:23.520
And in a way, that's even
like the best part of it.

00:57:23.520 --> 00:57:26.199
So it's a very modest program.

00:57:26.199 --> 00:57:27.740
We're not trying to
change the world.

00:57:27.740 --> 00:57:30.530
But I don't think you can
have too many people working

00:57:30.530 --> 00:57:31.570
on this.

00:57:31.570 --> 00:57:33.600
Ours is just like maybe
at the end of the year,

00:57:33.600 --> 00:57:35.880
200 kids know how
to feed themself

00:57:35.880 --> 00:57:38.270
a little bit better
than they did before.

00:57:38.270 --> 00:57:39.990
I think that's pretty great.

00:57:39.990 --> 00:57:42.610
MALE SPEAKER: What do you
tell, with the outbreak

00:57:42.610 --> 00:57:45.514
of the celebrity chef,
certainly, there's

00:57:45.514 --> 00:57:46.180
the television--

00:57:46.180 --> 00:57:48.639
DANIEL PATTERSON: Like a virus.

00:57:48.639 --> 00:57:50.180
MALE SPEAKER: I
mean, to some extent,

00:57:50.180 --> 00:57:53.900
I mean, I know Bobby
Flay, Morimoto.

00:57:53.900 --> 00:57:55.779
I know that they can cook.

00:57:55.779 --> 00:57:56.570
I do not know them.

00:57:56.570 --> 00:57:58.210
But I know that they can cook.

00:57:58.210 --> 00:58:00.770
They did not get there
because they couldn't.

00:58:00.770 --> 00:58:03.950
I know that there's
plenty of chefs on TV

00:58:03.950 --> 00:58:09.700
that are great personalities
and are able to excite people.

00:58:09.700 --> 00:58:13.560
I also know that I
have kids from 10 to 20

00:58:13.560 --> 00:58:18.360
coming up to me saying,
I want to be a chef.

00:58:18.360 --> 00:58:22.590
DANIEL PATTERSON:
Well, every development

00:58:22.590 --> 00:58:25.510
that's new in culture
has good things

00:58:25.510 --> 00:58:28.000
and it always has side effects.

00:58:28.000 --> 00:58:30.530
You don't get any
forward movement

00:58:30.530 --> 00:58:34.240
without a little bit of
negative side effect.

00:58:34.240 --> 00:58:44.560
This fetishization of
chefs is like crazy time.

00:58:44.560 --> 00:58:48.100
We're manual laborers.

00:58:48.100 --> 00:58:52.160
We're like the people who
lay carpet or paint walls

00:58:52.160 --> 00:58:55.540
or put woodwork in.

00:58:55.540 --> 00:58:56.860
That's our job.

00:58:56.860 --> 00:58:59.360
Our job really hasn't
changed for 100 years.

00:58:59.360 --> 00:59:01.100
Our perception of
the job was changed.

00:59:01.100 --> 00:59:03.910
But at the end of the day, we
don't have coal in our ovens

00:59:03.910 --> 00:59:04.410
anymore.

00:59:04.410 --> 00:59:05.700
So that's a big improvement.

00:59:05.700 --> 00:59:09.220
MALE SPEAKER: Sometimes you
do now in flavoring things.

00:59:09.220 --> 00:59:10.470
DANIEL PATTERSON: That's true.

00:59:10.470 --> 00:59:12.360
But at least we're
not breathing it in.

00:59:12.360 --> 00:59:17.510
But I think our approach is
much more human in the kitchen.

00:59:17.510 --> 00:59:23.560
We're much more cognizant of
people's emotional development.

00:59:23.560 --> 00:59:28.580
I always think, how do I
create an environment that

00:59:28.580 --> 00:59:32.050
supports people to be
as good as they can be?

00:59:32.050 --> 00:59:33.550
So we're thinking
about these things

00:59:33.550 --> 00:59:34.860
a lot more than we used to.

00:59:34.860 --> 00:59:36.720
But the basic job is the same.

00:59:36.720 --> 00:59:39.470
You have raw ingredients
that you transform into food.

00:59:39.470 --> 00:59:42.020
And it takes a lot of
work and a lot of hours.

00:59:42.020 --> 00:59:46.260
So however that's
being contextualized,

00:59:46.260 --> 00:59:48.590
to the extent that it
brings people closer

00:59:48.590 --> 00:59:50.970
to thinking about what
they put in their bodies,

00:59:50.970 --> 00:59:52.090
I think it's great.

00:59:52.090 --> 00:59:55.220
And if a little bit
of that is that people

00:59:55.220 --> 00:59:58.405
have this idea that it's a
glamorous profession, ah, come

00:59:58.405 --> 01:00:01.160
on, they'll learn soon enough.

01:00:01.160 --> 01:00:02.810
MALE SPEAKER: Hear, hear.

01:00:02.810 --> 01:00:05.340
Thank you so much for
allowing me to host this

01:00:05.340 --> 01:00:07.140
and for coming to San Francisco.

01:00:07.140 --> 01:00:07.940
DANIEL PATTERSON:
Thank you so much--

01:00:07.940 --> 01:00:08.670
MALE SPEAKER: It was
an absolute pleasure.

01:00:08.670 --> 01:00:09.570
DANIEL PATTERSON:
--for having me.

01:00:09.570 --> 01:00:10.070
[APPLAUSE]

01:00:10.070 --> 01:00:12.020
DANIEL PATTERSON: Hey,
thanks for coming.

